Security: lock down books catalog + harden auth routing

CRITICAL FIX — books catalog vandalism:
- The books table RLS allowed any authenticated user to INSERT/UPDATE any row
  via the REST API (USING (true)), so a stolen-less attack with any logged-in
  token could rewrite every book's title/author/description. The whole catalog
  had been overwritten to "test".
- All book-catalog writes moved server-side: new authenticated POST
  /api/books/ensure (service-role find-or-create from Google Books). The four
  client write sites (addGoogleBookToShelf, recommend, both post composers) now
  call it; the browser no longer writes to public.books.
- Migration 20260618000004 drops the books INSERT/UPDATE policies (default-deny);
  reads stay open. Verified: client UPDATE/INSERT now rejected, ensure works.

Routing / history hardening (back button no longer lands on auth pages):
- onboardingRedirectGuard: already-onboarded users are bounced off
  /onboarding/genres to /home.
- Transient auth pages use replaceUrl on success (login, signup verify, OAuth
  callback, onboarding) so they leave the history stack.
- guestGuard (added earlier) keeps authenticated users off / and /signup.

Tooling: catalog-repair + diagnostic scripts under backend/scripts/.

